WEBVTT

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:25.000
HAS BROUGHT WITH IT
 THE LARGEST MOVEMENT OF PEOPLE

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:27.000
IN THE HISTORY
 OF MODERN TIMES.

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:29.000
EVERYWHERE, MILLIONS
 OF PEOPLE ARE ON THEIR WAY

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:30.000
TO SOMEWHERE NEW.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:33.000
NO WALL OR BARRIER IS
 STRONG ENOUGH TO STOP MIGRANTS

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:35.000
AS THEY CROSS
 INTERNATIONAL BORDERS

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:38.000
ON A JOURNEY TO WHERE
 THE ACTION IS:

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:40.000
THE GLOBAL CITIES.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:46.000
[PEOPLE CHEERING, SHOUTING]

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:51.000
NARRATOR: MEXICO CITY IS
 AN URGENT, OVERCROWDED CITY.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:54.000
THE MOST POPULATED METROPOLIS
 IN THE WORLD,

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:58.000
20 MILLION PEOPLE
 CALL MEXICO CITY HOME.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:01.000
THIS IS A CITY
 OF CONTRASTS.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:06.000
HERE, YOU FIND THE WORLD
 OF GLOBALIZATION...

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:09.000
AND A WORLD OF SLUMS

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:11.000
AND OPEN-AIR MARKETS.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:13.000
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:17.000
IN MEXICO CITY,
 THE BENEFITS OF GLOBALIZATION

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:20.000
ARE UNEVENLY DISTRIBUTED.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:22.000
THE WINNERS
 OF GLOBALIZATION

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:24.000
ENJOY A HIGH STANDARD
 OF LIVING

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:27.000
AND ALL THE LUXURIES
 OF THE MODERN WORLD.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:29.000
[WOMAN SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:31.000
[WOMAN TRANSLATING IVANOVA]
 YOU FIND EVERYTHING HERE--

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:32.000
SHOPPING MALLS
 WITH HIGH FASHION,

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:34.000
LIKE YOU FIND
 EVERYWHERE IN THE WORLD,

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:37.000
BUT THE PRICES
 ARE A BIT HIGHER.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:39.000
NARRATOR:
 THE GLOBALIZATION LOSERS,

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:41.000
MOSTLY NATIVE PEOPLE

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:43.000
WHO MIGRATED TO THE BIG CITY
 LOOKING FOR WORK,

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:47.000
FIND ALL BUT THE LOWEST-PAID
 JOBS CLOSED TO THEM,

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:50.000
SO THEY HAVE TO INVENT
 WAYS TO SURVIVE.

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:53.000
[MAN SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:56.000
[MAN TRANSLATING CRUZ]
 I LOOK AFTER PEOPLE'S CARS.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:01.000
I MAKE SURE NO ONE STEALS THEM
 OR THE POLICE TOWS THEM AWAY.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:03.000
I'M SUPPOSED TO GET
 A DOLLAR A DAY,

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:05.000
BUT SOMETIMES PEOPLE
 ONLY GIVE ME

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:08.000
20 CENTS
 FOR THE WHOLE DAY,

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:12.000
AND VERY OFTEN THEY
 DON'T EVEN SAY "THANK YOU."

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:13.000
THEY JUST DRIVE AWAY.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:15.000
[CAR HORN HONKING]

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:17.000
[WOMAN SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:19.000
[WOMAN TRANSLATING]
 TO HELP MY PARENTS,

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:20.000
I SELL CALLING CARDS
 FOR CELL PHONES.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:22.000
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:24.000
THEY PAY ME SIX PESOS

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:27.000
FOR EACH HUNDRED-PESO CARD
 THAT I SELL.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:32.000
I MAKE ABOUT
 SEVEN DOLLARS A DAY.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:40.000
NARRATOR: WITH GLOBALIZATION,
 MEXICO HAS BECOME

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:43.000
ONE OF THE WORLD'S
 MOST ACTIVE TRADING NATIONS.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:45.000
ITS EXPORTS
 HAVE RISEN DRAMATICALLY

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:50.000
FROM 52 BILLION DOLLARS A YEAR
 TO 275 BILLION.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:52.000
AND MEXICO IS
 THE LARGEST RECIPIENT

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:54.000
OF FOREIGN INVESTMENT
 IN LATIN AMERICA.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:56.000
MAN: I THINK
 MEXICO HAS BEEN

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:59.000
A GOOD PLACE TO INVEST
 MOST OF THE TIME.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:01.000
AND I THINK
ONE OF THE REASONS

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:03.000
THAT MEXICO IS
A GOOD PLACE TO INVEST

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:05.000
IS OUR POLITICAL STABILITY.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:09.000
WE ARE A COUNTRY
WITH A DEMOCRATIC GOVERNMENT.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:13.000
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:16.000
[MAN TRANSLATING] THERE IS
 NO DEMOCRACY OR EQUALITY HERE

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:20.000
BECAUSE 85 PERCENT
 OF THE PEOPLE ARE POOR

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:22.000
AND, ON TOP OF THAT,
 THE INDIAN PEOPLE

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:27.000
ARE VERY OFTEN
 DISCRIMINATED AGAINST.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:29.000
[IVANOVA SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:32.000
[WOMAN TRANSLATING]
 A LOT OF TIMES,

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:34.000
I CAN HEAR MEXICANS SAY
 BAD THINGS ABOUT INDIANS.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:38.000
I DO BELIEVE
 THERE IS DISCRIMINATION.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:42.000
IT'S SOMETHING THAT THEY
 CARRY DEEP INSIDE THEM.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:46.000
AND I THINK THERE IS A BIG
 CONFLICT BETWEEN MEXICANS,

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:48.000
BUT, AS A FOREIGNER,

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:50.000
I CAN'T BE PART
 OF THAT CONFLICT.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:54.000
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:56.000
[MAN TRANSLATING DESCOMBEY]
 AS AN INVOLVED FOREIGNER,

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:59.000
I SEE THIS CONFLICT
 AS ONE OF HUMANRIGHTS.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:02.000
WHEN WE TALK ABOUT
 HUMAN RIGHTS,

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:05.000
WE USUALLY
 TALK ABOUT TORTURE.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:06.000
BUT HERE IN MEXICO CITY,

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:09.000
THE HUMAN RIGHTS
 OF MILLIONS OF PEOPLE

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:10.000
WHO LIVE IN EXTREME POVERTY

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:14.000
ARE BEING VIOLATED EVERY DAY,

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:19.000
AND I THINK A DECENT LIVING
 IS ALSO A HUMAN RIGHT.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:25.000
[MAN SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:27.000
[MAN TRANSLATING]
 I GO AROUND THE STREETS

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:30.000
WITH MY CART
 PICKING UP GARBAGE.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:36.000
I MANAGE TWO TRIPS TO THE DUMP
 A DAY, SEVEN DAYS A WEEK.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:38.000
PEOPLE PAY ME
 WHATEVER THEY WANT.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:39.000
I MAKE ABOUT
 FIVE DOLLARS A DAY.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:44.000
NARRATOR:
 IN MEXICO CITY,

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:47.000
POVERTY HAS REACHED
 CRISIS PROPORTIONS.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:50.000
66 PERCENT OF ITS INHABITANTS
 ARE CONSIDERED POOR

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:55.000
AND 30 PERCENT OF THEM LIVE
 ON LESS THAN TWO DOLLARS A DAY.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:58.000
THE PROBLEM IS NOT
 THAT MEXICO IS

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:00.000
A POOR COUNTRY
 WITHOUT RESOURCES.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:03.000
THE PROBLEM IS A BAD SYSTEM
 OF DISTRIBUTING WEALTH.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:05.000
AND POVERTY IS INCREASING

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:07.000
DESPITE A HIGHER
 EDUCATIONAL LEVEL

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:10.000
IN THE POPULATION
 AS A WHOLE.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:12.000
IT SEEMS THAT
 A BETTER EDUCATION

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:13.000
DOES NOT NECESSARILY MEAN

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:16.000
A MEXICAN CAN ESCAPE
 A LIFE OF POVERTY.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:17.000
[MAN SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:19.000
[MAN TRANSLATING]
 I'M A PSYCHOLOGIST,

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:20.000
BUT HERE IN MEXICO CITY

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:22.000
THERE ARE NO JOBS
 IN MY PROFESSION,

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:24.000
SO I HAVE TO WORK
 WITH GARBAGE.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:27.000
[MAN SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:28.000
TRANSLATOR:
 I MAKE MORE HERE

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:31.000
DIVING FOR STUFF
 THAT I THEN SELL FOR RECYCLING

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:34.000
THAN AS A PSYCHOLOGIST.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:37.000
[MORALES SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:39.000
THEY ONLY MAKE
 ABOUT 40 DOLLARS A WEEK,

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:42.000
NOT EVEN ENOUGH
 TO FEED YOUR FAMILY.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:47.000
NARRATOR:
 IN MEXICO CITY,

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:49.000
GLOBALIZATION HAS
 SHARPLY INCREASED

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:52.000
THE DISPARITY
 BETWEEN RICH AND POOR.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:54.000
BUT ECONOMIC GROWTH
 IN MEXICO

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:57.000
AT AROUND 6.5 PERCENT
 A YEAR IS STRONG,

00:05:57.000 --> 00:05:59.000
AND IT'S ONLY ONE
 OF THE MANY FACTORS

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:03.000
ATTRACTING FOREIGN INVESTORS.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:05.000
[MAN SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:06.000
[MAN TRANSLATING ZORILLA]
 WE'RE IN THE FOREFRONT

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:08.000
AS AN ELECTRONIC MARKET

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:10.000
WITH METHODS OF OPERATION
 IN TECHNOLOGY

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:12.000
ON THE SAME LEVEL WITH THE MAIN
 GLOBAL FINANCIAL MARKETS.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:16.000
[ZORILLA SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:18.000
TRANSLATOR: THIS ALLOWS US
 TO ATTRACT INVESTORS

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:20.000
AND TO WORK
 WITH PENSION FUNDS,

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:24.000
INVESTMENT BANKS
 AND VENTURE CAPITAL COMPANIES.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:26.000
NARRATOR:
 MEXICO IS THE DARLING

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:28.000
OF THE LEGION
 OF GLOBAL INVESTORS

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:30.000
WHO CAN COLLECTIVELY TOPPLE
 OR SEND BOOMING

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:33.000
THE ECONOMIES
 OF DEVELOPING COUNTRIES

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:35.000
WITH A FEW CLICKS
 OF A COMPUTER MOUSE.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:37.000
THE MAIN ATTRACTION
 ARE THE BARGAINS

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:40.000
IN MEXICO CITY'S STOCK MARKET.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:41.000
HERE, YOU CAN INVEST IN STOCKS

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:44.000
THAT GENERATE DOLLAR INCOME
 FROM SAFE SOURCES.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:47.000
NARRATOR: INVESTORS
 GET THE KIND OF SAFETY

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:49.000
THEY FIND IN NORTH AMERICA
 OR EUROPE

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:51.000
BUT WITH MUCH HIGHER RETURNS.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:55.000
[ZORILLA SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:57.000
TRANSLATOR:
 HERE IN MEXICO,

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:00.000
WE NOW HAVE POLITICAL STABILITY
 AND SOUND ECONOMIC POLICIES.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:02.000
THIS HAS GENERATED
 A POSITIVE FRAMEWORK

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:03.000
TO ATTRACT
 THE FLOW OF CAPITAL

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:05.000
AND TO ATTRACT
 FOREIGN INVESTORS.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:08.000
[TRAFFIC NOISES]

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:11.000
NARRATOR: IN A GLOBALIZED,
 INTERDEPENDENT ECONOMY,

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:14.000
MEXICO'S REAL ATTRACTION
 TO FOREIGN INVESTORS

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:17.000
IS NOT POLITICAL STABILITY
 OR SOUND ECONOMIC POLICIES

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:20.000
BUT A LOW-WAGE WORK FORCE

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:22.000
CAPABLE OF PERFORMING WELL,

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:23.000
LEARN AND TRAIN QUICKLY

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:26.000
AND DELIVER
 WORLD-CLASS PRODUCTS.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:30.000
[SPEAKING GERMAN]

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:32.000
TRANSLATOR:
 THE ONLY REASON

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:33.000
WHY WE MOVED
 OUR PRODUCTION FACILITIES

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:36.000
FROM GERMANY TO MEXICO CITY
 IS SALARIES.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:38.000
[DEWITZ SPEAKING GERMAN]

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:41.000
TRANSLATOR: WHILE IN GERMANY
 WE HAVE TO PAY A SKILLED WORKER

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:45.000
FROM 35 TO 40 DOLLARS AN HOUR,

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:47.000
HERE IN MEXICO CITY
 WE PAY THAT SAME WORKER

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:50.000
FIVE OR SIX DOLLARS A DAY.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:54.000
NARRATOR: AND TO EARN
 THIS BASIC PAY,

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:56.000
A WORKER IN MEXICO CITY

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:59.000
CAN TAKE UP TO FOUR HOURS
 TO GET TO HIS JOB.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:01.000
[WHISTLE BLOWING]

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:05.000
RUSH HOUR IS AN ORDEAL
 IN THIS IMPOSSIBLE METROPOLIS,

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:07.000
AND THE ARGUMENT OVER HOW
 TO GET THE CITY MOVING

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:11.000
BREAKS DOWN SHARPLY
 ALONG RACE AND CLASS LINES.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:13.000
PEOPLE WHO ARE RICHER

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:15.000
AND, TO PUT IT BLUNTLY, WHITER,

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:17.000
WITH MORE SPANISH
 THAN INDIAN BLOOD,

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:20.000
TEND TO FAVOR THE IDEA
 OF MORE HIGHWAYS.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:22.000
PEOPLE WHO ARE
 POORER AND BROWNER

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:26.000
WOULD LIKE TO HAVE
 MORE PUBLIC TRANSPORTATION.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:28.000
[CAR HORN HONKING]

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:30.000
PEOPLE WHO ARE
 POORER AND BROWNER

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:32.000
WOULD ALSO LIKE
 TO HAVE THE RIGHT

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:34.000
TO SELL ON THE STREETS.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:36.000
PEOPLE WHO ARE
 RICHER AND WHITER

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:39.000
ARE AGAINST SELLING
 ON THE STREETS.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:41.000
WE ARE WORKING
WITH THE GOVERNMENT.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:42.000
NOW WE JUST STARTED

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:45.000
IN THE HISTORICAL DISTRICT
OF MEXICO CITY

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:48.000
A NEW PROGRAM
WITH THE MAYOR.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:52.000
AND MOVING THE PEOPLE
WHO SELL ON THE STREETS

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:53.000
IS PART OF THE PROJECT.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:56.000
AND WE WILL BE EXPECTING

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:59.000
THAT IN THE NEXT FEW MONTHS

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:03.000
THEY ARE NOT GOING
 TO BE THERE ANYMORE.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:06.000
NARRATOR:
 NO ONE REALLY KNOWS

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:08.000
HOW MANY VENDORS WORK
 THE STREETS OF MEXICO CITY.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:12.000
ESTIMATES RANGE FROM
 2 TO 2.5 MILLION.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:14.000
AND AS THE CITY GOVERNMENT

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:16.000
PREPARES A PLAN TO BAN THEM
 FROM THE CITY CENTER,

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:19.000
DAILY PROTESTS BY VENDORS
 AND THEIR SUPPORTERS

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:21.000
GO BEYOND THE OBVIOUS DEMANDS

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:23.000
FOR FREEDOM TO SELL
 IN THE STREETS.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:26.000
THESE PEOPLE ARE ALSO
 ELOQUENTLY CONDEMNING

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.000
A DIVIDED AND UNEQUAL SOCIETY.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:34.000
[CROWD SHOUTING IN SPANISH]

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:37.000
[WOMAN SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:41.000
TRANSLATOR: IN 1994, I CAME
 TO WORK WITH MY MOTHER.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:45.000
SHE'S BEEN SELLING TACOS
 HERE FOR 27 YEARS,

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:48.000
SO I ALSO STARTED
 SELLING TACOS.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:49.000
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:51.000
TRANSLATOR: THIS IS
 OUR PERMANENT PLACE,

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:53.000
AND THE CITY
 HAS TO RESPECT IT

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:58.000
BECAUSE NOW WE KNOW
 HOW TO DEFEND OURSELVES

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:01.000
AND WE WILL NOT BE MADE FOOLS
 BY FALSE LEADERS AGAIN.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:03.000
WE WILL NOT ALLOW POLICEMEN
 TO COME AND TELL US,

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:06.000
"GIVE ME SOME MONEY, OR
 I'LL KICK YOU OUT OF HERE."

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:08.000
NOW WE KNOW OUR RIGHTS.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:11.000
[PROTESTORS CHANTING]

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:13.000
TRANSLATOR:
 NOW WE HAVE A PERMIT

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:15.000
TO SELL TACOS
 ON THIS CORNER,

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:17.000
BUT I STILL SEE
 THE POLICE COMING HERE

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:21.000
AND TAKING AWAY THE MERCHANDISE
 OF MANY VENDORS.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:23.000
OFTEN, THEY ALSO BEAT THEM UP.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:25.000
THERE ARE SOME POLICEMEN
 WHO STILL DO THAT.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:31.000
[PROTESTORS SHOUTING]

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:33.000
NARRATOR:
 ONLY TWO KILOMETERS AWAY

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.000
FROM WHERE THE STREET VENDORS
 ARE CLASHING WITH RIOT POLICE,

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:37.000
BUT ON ANOTHER PLANET,

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:39.000
COPARMEX, A BUSINESS UNION

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:40.000
WHOSE MEMBERSHIP INCLUDES

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:43.000
SOME OF THE LARGEST
 CORPORATIONS IN MEXICO CITY,

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:45.000
IS HOLDING
 ITS ANNUAL CONVENTION.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:48.000
[APPLAUSE]

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:50.000
[WOMAN SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:52.000
[WOMAN TRANSLATING BECERRIL]
 CORPORATE EXECUTIVES

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:54.000
ARE THE FOURTH POWER
 IN THIS COUNTRY,

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:58.000
BECAUSE IF ONE OF THEM SAYS,
 "I DON'T LIKE THIS POLICY,"

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:02.000
AND THREATENS TO TAKE
 HIS INVESTMENTS OUT OF MEXICO,

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:04.000
THE GOVERNMENT IS FORCED
 TO PAY ATTENTION

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:06.000
AND HAS TO CHANGE
 THAT POLICY.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:09.000
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:11.000
ARRIAGA:
 WE FEEL THAT WE LIVE

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:14.000
IN A QUITE
MORE DEMOCRATIC COUNTRY,

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:18.000
AND LIVING IN A DEMOCRACY
HAS THOSE SITUATIONS.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:21.000
YOU HAVE TO FACE SITUATIONS
THAT YOU DON'T LIKE,

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:24.000
BUT YOU HAVE TO FACE THEM,
 AND TRY TO WORK WITH THEM,

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:26.000
AND TRY TO UNDERSTAND THEM,

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:29.000
AND TRY TO PURSUE THEM
ON WHAT YOU FEEL IS IMPORTANT.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:32.000
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:35.000
TRANSLATOR: IN MEXICO,
 THE WINNERS OF GLOBALIZATION

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:38.000
ARE THE RICH
 AND THE BIG CORPORATIONS

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:41.000
THAT HAVE ACCESS
 TO THE GLOBAL MARKET.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:45.000
IN THIS COUNTRY,
 ONLY 300 COMPANIES EXPORT.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:48.000
NINETY PERCENT OF ALL MEXICAN
 EXPORTS ARE IN THEIR HANDS.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:52.000
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:56.000
THE BIG LOSER OF GLOBALIZATION
 IS THE MIDDLE CLASS.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:58.000
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:11:58.000 --> 00:11:59.000
TRANSLATOR:
 IN MEXICO CITY,

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:02.000
THERE ARE NO LONGER
 OPPORTUNITIES FOR THESE PEOPLE.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:04.000
[BECERRIL CONTINUES
 IN SPANISH]

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:06.000
TRANSLATOR:
 YOU CAN OFTEN FIND

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:08.000
PEOPLE WITH
 A UNIVERSITY DEGREE,

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:12.000
EVEN MEDICAL DOCTORS,
 DRIVING A TAXI.

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:18.000
[WOMAN SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:21.000
TRANSLATOR: I HAVE BEEN
 LOOKING FOR A JOB FOR A MONTH.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:23.000
RIGHT NOW,
 HERE IN MEXICO CITY,

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:25.000
THERE IS LOTS OF UNEMPLOYMENT,

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:28.000
SO IT'S NOT EASY
 TO FIND A JOB.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:30.000
I LOOK FOR WORK EVERY DAY.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:33.000
I SEND MY CURRICULUM,
 GO TO INTERVIEWS,

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:35.000
BUT I CAN'T FIND ANYTHING.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:39.000
[RESENDIS CONTINUES
 IN SPANISH]

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:41.000
TRANSLATOR:
 I REALLY BELIEVE

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:43.000
THAT WE HAVE BEEN
 DEEPLY AFFECTED

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:45.000
BY THIS GLOBALIZATION THING.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:47.000
I DON'T REALLY
 EXPECT LUXURIES,

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:49.000
BUT I NEED A ROOF
 OVER MY HEAD,

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:52.000
A HOME WITH
 THE BASIC SERVICES--

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:54.000
YOU KNOW,
 ELECTRICITY, HOT WATER.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:57.000
THE MIDDLE CLASS
 HAS BEEN AFFECTED, YEAH,

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:01.000
BUT PEOPLE IN LOWER INCOME
 BRACKETS ARE DROWNING

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:03.000
BECAUSE THE PRICES
 SEEM TO SQUEEZE HARDER

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:06.000
ON THOSE WHO ARE POOR.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:13.000
[BOY SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:15.000
TRANSLATOR: HERE WITH
 MY BROTHER AND SISTER,

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:17.000
WE MAKE ABOUT
 TWO DOLLARS A DAY,

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:20.000
AND WE GIVE ALL THE MONEY
 TO OUR MOTHER TO BUY FOOD.

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.000
SOME PEOPLE GIVE GOOD TIPS,

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:26.000
BUT MOST PEOPLE
 GIVE US NOTHING.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:29.000
[TRAFFIC NOISES]

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:32.000
NARRATOR: MEXICO CITY
 IS A MODERN METROPOLIS,

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:36.000
BUT ALSO TEEMS
 WITH SIGNS OF ITS PAST.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:41.000
ITS CULTURE, INHERITED EQUALLY
 FROM THE SPANISH CONQUERORS

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:43.000
AND THEIR AZTEC ENEMIES,

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:47.000
MAKES IT MUCH MORE THAN
 JUST ANOTHER GLOBAL CITY.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:49.000
[MACHINERY HUMMING]

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:51.000
AN URGENCY TO MODERNIZE

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:54.000
HAS TORN DOWN
 MOST OF THE OLD STRUCTURES,

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:57.000
LEAVING ONLY
 AN OCCASIONAL SPANISH MANSION

00:13:57.000 --> 00:13:59.000
AMONG THE OFFICE TOWERS...

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:02.000
OR A SPLENDID CHURCH

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.000
HIGH AND DRY
 AMONG THE TRAFFIC JAMS.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:07.000
[CAR HORNS HONKING]

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:11.000
AND THE ONLY REMINDER
 OF THE IMPERIAL CAPITAL

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:13.000
BUILT BY THE AZTECS

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:16.000
CENTURIES BEFORE THE ARRIVAL
 OF THE SPANISH CONQUERORS

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:20.000
IS THE FLOATING GARDENS
 OF XOCHIMILCO.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:26.000
[MAN SINGING IN SPANISH]

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:30.000
NARRATOR: XOCHIMILCO WITH
 ITS 180 KILOMETERS OF CANALS

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:34.000
IS NOW A WEEKEND PLAYGROUND
 FOR MEXICO CITY'S MIDDLE CLASS.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:36.000
[SINGING CONTINUES]

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:39.000
[MAN SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:41.000
[MAN TRANSLATING RODRIGUEZ]
 XOCHIMILCO IS A GOOD PLACE

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:42.000
TO COME WITH YOUR FRIENDS,
 TO HAVE A GOOD TIME,

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:45.000
EAT TACOS,
 HAVE A FEW DRINKS OF TEQUILA,

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:47.000
LISTEN TO MARIACHI MUSIC.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:50.000
WE LIKE TO HAVE MANY FRIENDS.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.000
WE'RE A HAPPY-GO-LUCKY PEOPLE.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:56.000
[SINGING CONTINUES]

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:58.000
NARRATOR: THE FLOATING GARDENS
 OF XOCHIMILCO

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:00.000
ALSO ATTRACT
 THE INDIAN MIGRANTS

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:02.000
LIVING IN MEXICO CITY.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.000
[SHOUTING IN SPANISH]

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:06.000
NARRATOR:
 ESPECIALLY ON WEEKENDS,

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:09.000
THOUSANDS COME TO BUY AND SELL
 IN THESE OPEN-AIR MARKETS.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:13.000
BUT IT'S NOT JUST ABOUT
 BUYING AND SELLING.

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:16.000
IT'S THE SOUNDS, THE SMELLS

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:19.000
AND THE SENTIMENTAL MEMORY OF
 THE VILLAGES THEY LEFT BEHIND

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:21.000
WHEN THEY MIGRATED
 TO THE BIG CITY.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:26.000
AS OPPOSED
 TO OTHER GLOBAL CITIES,

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:28.000
WHERE MIGRANTS COME
 FROM OTHER COUNTRIES,

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:31.000
THE FACE OF MEXICO CITY
 IS BEING CHANGED

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:33.000
BY MILLIONS
 OF INDIAN MIGRANTS

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:35.000
WHO'VE COME FROM OTHER REGIONS
 IN MEXICO.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:38.000
THE NATIVE PEOPLE

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:40.000
WHO FOR GENERATIONS,
 CENTURIES EVEN,

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:42.000
HAVE BOWED DOWN TO AUTHORITY,

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:44.000
ARE NOW TAKING TO THE STREETS

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:48.000
AND HOLDING THOSE IN POWER
 RESPONSIBLE FOR THEIR ACTIONS.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:49.000
[MAN SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:52.000
TRANSLATOR: WE'VE BEEN CAMPING
 HERE FOR SIX WEEKS.

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:53.000
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:55.000
TRANSLATOR:
 WE'RE DEMANDING AN AMNESTY

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:57.000
TO LIBERATE 20 MEN
 OF OUR VILLAGE

00:15:57.000 --> 00:15:59.000
WHO ARE ACCUSED
 OF COLLABORATING

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:00.000
WITH THE ZAPATISTA REBELS.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.000
[GUERRERO CONTINUES
 IN SPANISH]

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:04.000
TRANSLATOR: WE'RE ALSO
 DEMANDING AN AMNESTY

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:07.000
FOR ALL OTHER
 POLITICAL PRISONERS.

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:09.000
[SIREN WAILING]

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:11.000
NARRATOR:
 AMONG THE NATIVES

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:12.000
CAMPING IN MEXICO CITY'S
 MAIN SQUARE

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:14.000
IS FRANCISCO LOPEZ

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:16.000
WHO HAS JUST BEEN RELEASED
 FROM TWO YEARS IN PRISON

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:19.000
ON SUSPICION
 OF SUBVERSIVE ACTIVITIES.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:21.000
[LOPEZ SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:25.000
TRANSLATOR: WE HAVEN'T
 DONE ANYTHING WRONG.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:27.000
WE JUST ASKED FOR HELP
 FROM THE GOVERNMENT,

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:30.000
AND INSTEAD,
 THEY THREW US IN JAIL.

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:32.000
[LOPEZ CONTINUING
 IN SPANISH]

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:35.000
TRANSLATOR: MY SON AND
 MANY OTHERS ARE STILL IN JAIL.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:37.000
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:39.000
TRANSLATOR: WE WANT
 OUR FRIENDS TO BE FREE.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:42.000
NARRATOR: IN 1997,

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:44.000
THIS ABANDONED
 HISTORICAL BUILDING

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:45.000
IN DOWNTOWN MEXICO CITY

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:49.000
WAS OCCUPIED BY 49 HOMELESS
 INDIGENOUS FAMILIES

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:52.000
WHO REFUSED
 TO LEAVE THE BUILDING.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:54.000
IN THE MIGRANT COMMUNITIES
 OF MEXICO CITY,

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:57.000
AS KIDS,
 WOMAN OBEY THEIR FATHERS.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:00.000
AS TEENAGERS, THEIR FATHERS
 AND THEIR BROTHERS;

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:03.000
WHEN MARRIED, THEIR HUSBANDS;

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:06.000
AND AS OLD LADIES,
 THEIR SONS.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:09.000
IN THE OLDEN DAYS, NATIVE WOMEN
 FOLLOWED THIS PATTERN,

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:11.000
BUT THEY ARE NOW
 LEAVING IT BEHIND,

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:14.000
AND THEY'RE EMERGING
 AS THE ENGINE OF CHANGE.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:16.000
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:18.000
[WOMAN TRANSLATING MAYA]
 WE OCCUPIED THIS BUILDING

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:20.000
WHEN WE REALIZED THAT,
 AS INDIGENOUS WOMEN,

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:21.000
WE HAD TO ORGANIZE OURSELVES.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:24.000
[MAYA CONTINUES IN SPANISH]

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:25.000
TRANSLATOR:
 OUR OBJECTIVE IS

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:27.000
TO FIGHT FOR
 A DECENT PLACE TO LIVE.

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:29.000
THE UPRISING
 OF OUR ZAPATISTA BROTHERS

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:32.000
GAVE US THE IDEA
 THAT WE ALSO HAVE RIGHTS.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:34.000
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:36.000
TRANSLATOR: WE'RE ACCUSED
 OF BEING ZAPATISTAS

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:38.000
BECAUSE WE'RE INDIANS
 AND WE ARE POOR.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:40.000
THAT'S OUR CRIME.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:42.000
AND BECAUSE
 WE SPEAK THE TRUTH,

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:44.000
AND BECAUSE HERE IN MEXICO

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:46.000
A FEW PEOPLE HAVE
 ALL THE ECONOMIC POWER,

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:48.000
BUT MOST OF US ARE POOR.

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:51.000
[GUNFIRE, SHOUTING]

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:54.000
NARRATOR: IN 1994,
 THE ZAPATISTA REBELS

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:56.000
BEGAN AN UPRISING
 OVER INDIGENOUS RIGHTS

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:59.000
IN THE SOUTHEASTERN STATE
 OF CHIAPAS.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:02.000
THE ZAPATISTAS
 STOPPED FIGHTING

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:04.000
AFTER THE FIRST TWO WEEKS
 OF THEIR REBELLION,

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:07.000
BUT THEIR UPRISING CONTINUES.

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:08.000
TO END THEIR REBELLION,

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:10.000
THE ZAPATISTAS
 ARE DEMANDING LAWS

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:14.000
THAT PROTECT
 INDIGENOUS RIGHTS AND CULTURE.

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:19.000
THE INTERNATIONAL CIRCULATION
 THROUGH THE WEB

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:21.000
OF THE ZAPATISTA REBELLION
 IN MEXICO

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:24.000
HAS BECOME ONE OF
 THE MOST SUCCESSFUL EXAMPLES

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:26.000
OF THE USE
 OF COMPUTER TECHNOLOGY

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:29.000
BY AN INSURGENT GROUP.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:31.000
THE ZAPATISTAS
 HAVE EARNED THE NICKNAME

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:33.000
OF THE "INTERNET GUERRILLAS."

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:35.000
THEIR WEB NETWORK,

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:37.000
A CLEARINGHOUSE
 OF ZAPATISTA INFORMATION,

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:40.000
WITH SEVEN WEB SITES
 OF THEIR OWN

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:43.000
AND HUNDREDS OF SITES
 FROM INTERNATIONAL SUPPORTERS,

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:45.000
CONTINUES TO GROW.

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:49.000
IN MEXICO, AND ESPECIALLY
 IN MEXICO CITY,

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:50.000
MORE AND MORE YOUNG PEOPLE

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:53.000
SEE COMPUTER TECHNOLOGY
 AS A VEHICLE

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:56.000
TO BRING EQUALITY,
 PROSPERITY AND DEMOCRACY.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:01.000
[MAN SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:02.000
[MAN TRANSLATING ALOR]
 I LOOK AT NEW TECHNOLOGIES

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:04.000
AS A GREAT OPPORTUNITY

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:06.000
FOR AN UNDERDEVELOPED COUNTRY
 LIKE MEXICO TO GET AHEAD...

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:08.000
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:10.000
TRANSLATOR:
 IF THE BIG CORPORATIONS,

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:12.000
WHICH CONTROL TECHNOLOGY
 AND THE GOVERNMENT,

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:14.000
TURN TO LOOK AT THE PEOPLE
 WHO ARE POOR

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:16.000
AND TRY TO USE TECHNOLOGY

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:18.000
TO BRIDGE THE GAP
 BETWEEN RICH AND POOR.

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:20.000
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:22.000
TRANSLATOR: BECAUSE THE DIGITAL
 GAP WE HAVE IN MEXICO

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:26.000
IS A REFLECTION OF THE GAP
 BETWEEN RICH AND POOR,

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:28.000
THEN WE,
 AS INTERNET COMMUNICATORS,

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:30.000
CAN PLAY AN IMPORTANT ROLE.

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:32.000
[MAN SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:34.000
[MAN TRANSLATING REYES]
 TECHNOLOGY IS ALREADY BRIDGING

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:36.000
THE GAP BETWEEN RICH AND POOR

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:38.000
BECAUSE RICH OR POOR PEOPLE

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:40.000
ARE NOW USING
 THE SAME TECHNOLOGY.

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:42.000
WHOEVER WANTS TO SEND
 AN E-MAIL CAN DO IT

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:44.000
THROUGHOUT THE DAY.

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:46.000
WHETHER YOU'RE RICH OR POOR,

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:48.000
EVERYBODY IS INTERACTING
 WITH THE SAME TECHNOLOGY.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:52.000
MAN: THE PERCENTAGE
 OF KIDS USING COMPUTERS

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:53.000
IS REAL, REAL HIGH.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:59.000
PROBABLY FIVE OUT OF TEN KIDS
HAVE ACCESS TO INTERNET

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:00.000
AT THEIR FRIEND'S HOUSE,

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:04.000
OR AT THE SCHOOL,
OR IN A CYBER CAFé.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:08.000
KIDS ARE EXCHANGING
 DIGITAL MUSIC,

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:12.000
PICTURES,
 SOMETIMES EVEN VIDEOS,

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:15.000
WRITING E-MAIL, CHATTING,

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:17.000
SENDING INSTANT MESSAGING,

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:22.000
BUYING MOVIE THEATER TICKETS
 ON THE INTERNET.

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:24.000
AND THAT'S VERY COOL.

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:26.000
THAT'S SOMETHING
THAT'S HAPPENING OUT THERE.

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:28.000
[ELECTRONIC VOICE]
FIRE! FIRE!

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:29.000
[GUNFIRE]

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:34.000
[ALOR SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:36.000
TRANSLATOR: WE DECIDED
 TO LAUNCH A PLATFORM

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:38.000
THAT WOULD GO BEYOND
 JUST THE INTERNET,

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:40.000
A PLATFORM DIRECTED
 ESPECIALLY TO YOUNG PEOPLE,

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:42.000
A MEDIUM THAT TALKS TO THEM

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:44.000
ABOUT THE HUMAN SIDE
 OF TECHNOLOGY.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:46.000
WE DO COVER HIGH-TECH TOPICS

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:48.000
BUT FROM A DIFFERENT
 PERSPECTIVE.

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:50.000
WE DON'T LIMIT OURSELVES
 TO TECHNICAL ASPECTS.

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:53.000
WE ALSO OFFER
 SOME SOCIAL CONTENT.

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:55.000
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:57.000
TRANSLATOR:
 WE ALSO HAD THE IDEA

00:20:57.000 --> 00:20:59.000
TO MEXICANIZE
 THE DIGITAL CULTURE.

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:02.000
THAT'S WHY WE SEE TECHNOLOGY
 FROM A MORE HUMAN PERSPECTIVE

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:05.000
AND, ABOVE ALL,
 FROM A MEXICAN PERSPECTIVE.

00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:09.000
THIS MEXICANIZATION PROCESS
 INVOLVES TWO IMPORTANT ASPECTS:

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:11.000
FIRST, YOUR FEELING
 AS A MEXICAN,

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:13.000
AND SECOND,
 FINDING THE RESOURCES

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:15.000
THAT YOU NEED
 TO MAKE IT HAPPEN.

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:17.000
[ALOR SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:20.000
TRANSLATOR: YEAH,
 BECAUSE FOREIGN COMPANIES,

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:22.000
LIKE ZIFF DAVIS ORPC,
 CAN PLACE THEIR PRODUCT HERE...

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:27.000
BUT THEY'RE ONLY REMAKES
 FROM OTHER PARTS OF THE WORLD.

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:30.000
WHAT MAKES OUR PRODUCT UNIQUE
 IS ITS MEXICAN IDENTITY.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:35.000
[MAN SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:37.000
TRANSLATOR:
 FOR MANY YOUNG MEXICANS,

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:40.000
DIGITAL CULTURE HAS TRULY
 BECOME AN ECONOMIC ALTERNATIVE.

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:44.000
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:46.000
TRANSLATOR:
 BECAUSE THE ONLY OPTIONS

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:48.000
COMING FROM CORPORATIONS OR
 THE GOVERNMENT ARE UNEMPLOYMENT

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:50.000
OR SELLING WHATEVER YOU CAN
 ON THE STREETS,

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:52.000
WHILE DOT-COM TRAINING
 GIVES US THE OPTION

00:21:52.000 --> 00:21:53.000
TO PLACE MUSIC
 OR OTHER PRODUCTS

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:55.000
ON THE INTERNET MARKET

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:56.000
AND MAKE A GOOD,
 DECENT LIVING.

00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:58.000
[EXPLOSIONS ON COMPUTER]

